Wait... why did I make a log for this week?

Motionless/lazy phase

Well, first I was plotting this figure,

which is the phase diagram (a), with plotted states in (b)-(d). Here I realized that the purple region is not a disordered phase, but a Motionless one, i.e. in this region the system is either too quick, or the interactions are too weak to move the system into the GS. It just remains in whatever initial state the system is in.

  • Is the Motionless/Lazy phase equivalent to zero field?
  • This phase diagram should be quite different in a thermal setup as zero field configurations will disorder the system.

It is really clear how in (c), the system is partially ordered in an AF fashion.

Then I started plotting the topological charges by and see if there were clusters or something, and saw the following

Which is kind of what we expected. We were talking about a partially ordered phase in this region.

Question

However, it is kind of strange that there are almost only vertices. it feels as if that is supposed to happen at infinitely slow rotations.
Should this be the case? I am not sure, but I think it is not, if we look again at this figureontents

A pure AF2 state would have , and (b) shows its minimum below that, i.e. we should expect the OP to raise a bit as but the graphs shows no tendency for that.

But anyhow, this feels more like a rambling than an important thing.

Broken ergodicity

Personal reminder of our usual argument

After the previous text, I started pondering on whether the two green regions are of the same nature. My gut feeling is that they are not, but science is not made out of thin air, so here we go.

Putting into words our usual argument, the free energy

The minimum of is the same as , so

Thus, our usual argument of "increasing the field is the same as lowering the temperature"

And how does that relate?

I will go back a bit to the usual discrete version of the diagram. This is done by setting everything that is not 0 or 1 with 0.5 just to have three distinct zones.

Looking at figures, the green region that connects the Motionless and AF phases feels more like a transitory since clusters of charged arise until they go reach the GS. This is like... normal behavior.

Although, for example, at 12mT, we have again a partially ordered state, it is a transitory towards the AF ground state.

Question

How would melting look like?

However, this poses a problem. All of these experiments are done at constant and , i.e. the dashed line does not really connect any of these phases by some dynamic path in the phase space of these parameters.

Question

Can we transition from the initial state to the GS with a quenched protocol? something of the form

with being some rotation with constant . My gut tells me yes, but this system has proven us wrong several times by now.

Fun begins when we go very slow, as we get something like

then, no matter how much we cool the system, from the phase diagram alone we can tell that the GS is not accessible, a phenomenology quintessential to broken ergodicity. Remarkably, the non-ergodic zone grows linearly with the field magnitude, making it more difficult to reach the GS at higher fields with slow rotations.

Question

Is there a region in the phase diagram at constant where the system experiences all zones?

I think there should be a set of weird conditions in which this can happen. Although, with very high fields.

So, are the green regions of the same nature?
